{{Multiple issues| {{notability|date=August 2016}} {{more citations needed|date=January 2017}} }} {{Infobox video game | collapsible = | state = | italic title = y | title = Unnatural Selection | image = | alt = | caption = | developer = [[Maxis]] | publisher = [[Maxis]] | series = | engine = | platforms = [[DOS]] | released = {{Video game release|WW|1993}} | genre = | modes = | director = | producer = | designer = | programmer = | artist = | writer = | composer = | cabinet = | arcade system = | cpu = | sound = | display = }} '''Unnatural Selection''' is a 1993 game for [[DOS]] by [[Maxis]].
==Gameplay== In the game, the player breeds mutant animals to fight battles.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mobygames.com/game/unnatural-selection|title=Unnatural Selection for DOS (1993) - MobyGames|publisher=}}</ref> The game has two phases, the first is the breeding phase in which in the player uses various objects and methods (food, drugs, radiation) etc to breed the animals which will fight future battles. The second is the battle phase in which the animals are deployed on the battlefield in order to combat those of a rogue scientist.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/UnnaturalSelectionDemo|title=Unnatural Selection Demo|first=|last=Maxis Software|date=1 January 1993|publisher=|via=Internet Archive}}</ref>
==Reception== {{Video game reviews | CGW = {{rating|3.5|5}}{{r|brooks199405}} | rev1 = ''[[GamePro#PC Games|Electronic Entertainment]]'' | rev1Score = 7 out of 10<ref name=e2>{{cite journal | title=''Unnatural Selection'' | author=DeMaria, Rusel | journal=[[GamePro#PC Games|Electronic Entertainment]] | date=March 1994 | volume=1 | number=3 | pages=86 }}</ref> }}
A 1994 ''[[Computer Gaming World]]'' survey of strategic space games set in the year 2000 and later gave the game three-plus stars out of five, stating that it was "A different concept, ''almost'' carried off with success".<ref name="brooks199405">{{Cite magazine |last=Brooks |first=M. Evan |author= |last2= |first2= |date=May 1994 |title=Never Trust A Gazfluvian Flingschnogger! |department= |url=http://www.cgwmuseum.org/galleries/index.php?year=1994&pub=2&id=118 |magazine=Computer Gaming World |pages=42–58}}</ref>
